questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput Spring Boot microservice is experiencing gradual heap exhaustion (OOM: Java heap space) and frequent Stop-The-World (STW) GCs. Profiling reveals millions of instances of `java.util.HashMap$Node` and heavy business payloads being retained in memory. The source code contains the following custom thread-context tracking mechanism:

java
@Component
public class RequestContextHolder {
    private static final ThreadLocal<Map<String, Object>> threadContext = ThreadLocal.withInitial(HashMap::new);

    public void put(String key, Object value) {
        threadContext.get().put(key, value);
    }

    public Object get(String key) {
        return threadContext.get().get(key);
    }
}

And a Spring MVC controller executing this logic:

java
@RestController
public class OrderController {
    @Autowired
    private RequestContextHolder contextHolder;

    @PostMapping("/orders")
    public ResponseEntity<Void> processOrder(@RequestBody Order order) {
        contextHolder.put("ORDER_DATA", order);
        // Business processing logic
        return ResponseEntity.ok().build();
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where an application leaks database connections and memory under heavy transactional load. The service uses Spring's `TransactionTemplate` alongside an injected custom thread pool to perform asynchronous database operations within a transactional block:

java
@Service
public class BatchProcessor {
    @Autowired private PlatformTransactionManager transactionManager;
    @Autowired private ExecutorService executorService;

    public void process(List<Task> tasks) {
        TransactionTemplate txTemplate = new TransactionTemplate(transactionManager);
        txTemplate.execute(status -> {
            for (Task task : tasks) {
                executorService.submit(() -> {
                    // Execute DB updates inside pool-managed thread
                    updateTaskStatus(task);
                });
            }
            return null;
        });
    } 
}

During peak load, heap dumps reveal a massive accumulation of unclosed connection objects and `SqlSessionTemplate` instances, causing connection pool exhaustion and Out-Of-Memory (OOM) errors.
